title: Show circles of estimate telemetry radio range
message:
Show circles of estimate telemetry radio range

Per Tridge's wiki entry:
If the 'rssi' and 'noise' levels meet on the graph then you will lose the link. To determine what your range would be, a rough rule of thumb is to subtract the 'rssi' and 'noise' numbers, then divide by 2. That tells you your "fade margin" in decibels. For each 6dB of fade margin your range doubles. So if you have 18dB of fade margin, then you will be able to do roughly 8x whatever range you were at when you measured the margin.

title: Add MavServe - an http server designed to serve data to Mavulous
message:
Add MavServe - an http server designed to serve data to Mavulous

Hi Pat,
Here ya go.  See MavServe.scala for a beginning class that you can use
as a starting point.  Search for FIXME to see particularly important
comments.

If you hook your 3dr radio to your desktop and then do "run" in posixpilot
you should be able to surf over to

http://localhost:4404/
And get a nice html welcome screen (you should slap all your JS etc... into
the new httpcontent directory (or change that directory to a symbolic
link while developing)

You'll see a couple of interesting links on the placeholder html.
One link will take you to vehicle params as JSON:

The other link will take you to some basic vehicle info:
http://localhost:4404/vehicle
If you fetch that URL you'll see more JSON:
{"loc":[37.5209667,-122.3090234,169.58],"attitude":[0.04189648,1.4802325,-0.057521753]}

You can add new REST endpoints by following the templates in MavServe.scala
- feel free to change anything you wish (anywhere in this project).

If you look at VehicleModel.scala you'll see it already captures a lot of
state that would be easy to expose to the JS world.  Also it publishes a
bunch of events when vehicle state changes.  See the placeholder I left
in MavServe for how to handle events.  Those events could be mapped to
a method that returns a 'comet style' endless stream of data to the client.

0.1.35

# 0.1.35
* Add settings option to control # of meter change needed for voice announcement (actually this was in 0.34)
* Shorten some mode names so they sound better
* Make usb host mode optional (so folks can use UDP on non host mode devices)
* Fix overview layout so it will look good on more devices
* Add preferences option to automatically back-up parameters to the SD card

For next release:
* Use new icons
* Do something to allow waypoint list selection with action bar ( http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3111354/android-listview-stay-selected )
* Show heartbeat lost on the overview screen
* FIXME: add waypoint change type (via menu dropdown)
* FIXME: make a website
* Change waypoint icons as appropriate...
* FIXME: Use a state machine to ensure we don't get confused if someone moves a waypoint while we are busy uploading new waypoints
* Clean up package namespace
* Show docs on parameter names (if possible)
* Handle the 'unusual' waypoint representations - look at mavproxy code for clues
* Use the following tip for sw testing: https://github.com/diydrones/ardupilot/commit/deb825b57583a4dd0fb8452ad0afdad07ab34c5b

0.1.34

# 0.1.34
* Add back nasty USB hack if urb.position is always zero (should fix at least android 4.0, probably 3.1)
* If usb hack needed, limit most mavlink streams to 1 hz
* Turn on direct zerocopy usb buffers
* Inbound UDP now works: Use this if your serial uplink is on some other machine (a different tablet or a PC)
* Outbound UDP now works: Use this if you want to share your serial link with some other machine
* Don't announce speech enabled when orientation changes
* Shorten many of the spoken phrases (but FIXME, haven't yet shortened mode names)
* Use urgent mode for speech of mode changes (to make sure this overrides batteryish msgs)
* In portrait mode, don't show the info pane - use swipes to switch between map etc...
* On phones never show info panels
